00000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of commissioners in reducing crime and delivering an effective police service within their police area</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My election manifesto and police and crime plan set out my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">priorities to reduce domestic burglary, rural crime, metal theft and prevent the criminal abuse of vulnerable people, whether they are adults or children.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The reduction in burglary has been exemplary, with an overall reduction of 20% in 2012/13 and a further reduction of 21% so far this year. The impact in Reading has been better, with burglary down 33% last year and a further 42% so far this year.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">So far this year rural crime is 16% lower than the comparable 8 month period last December. I have instructed the Force to focus, in particular, on the link between serious, organised crime and criminality and rural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crime</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (i.e. the theft of high value agricultural machinery</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The level of metal theft this year (April to November) is 43% lower than the same period last year. The Force has already undertaken at least 40 operations against metal theft this year, and more are planned for coming months.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Earlier this year the Force, working closely with partners, secured the conviction of 7 Asian men in the high profile trial at the Old Bailey (Operation Bullfinch) against child grooming in Oxford.  Dealing with this type of crime is one of my highest priorities and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> despite the significant budget reductions that I am </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to make</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> I have agreed with the Chief Constable that additional staff and financial resources will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alloca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ted to this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">priority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> area of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">activity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We are also in the process of establishing multi-agency safeguarding hubs across the Thames Valley area to deal with child abuse and child sexual exploitation.      </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">     </span></li></ol></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">B</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of commissioners in holding their chief constables to account</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thames Valley Police </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘Scheme of Corporate Governance’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> jointly agreed by me and the Chief Constable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> specifically refers to the statutory role of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, to hold the Chief Constable to account for the performance of the Force, including that of police officers and staff under her direction and control.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My role in holding the Chief Constable to account is as follows:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I developed my first four-year Police and Crime Plan in consultation with the Chief Constable to ensure it was informed by the Force’s strategic assessment of risks, threats and opportunities, and consistent with the Force’s operational service delivery plan in terms of shared policing priorities, strategic objectives and target outcomes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Having established common priorities and objectives, I then negotiated agreed performance measures and, where appropriate, performance targets that would enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regular and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">timely indications as to whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the policing policies, objectives and initiatives incorporated in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">my Plan </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are being successfully delivered by the Chief Constable and the Force under her direction and control.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The 2013/14 annual policing budget and medium-term financial plan covering the period 2013-2017</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was developed by the Chief Constable and presented to me for consideration and approval.  This process gave me the necessary assurance that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Chief Constable was fully committed to taking ownership of the approved policing budget, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the budget</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was sufficient to enable her to deliver the policing objectives set out in my Police and Crime Plan, and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the resources allocated to the Chief Constable would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">appropriately allocated and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deployed at an operational level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consistent with my strategic priorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(e.g. tackling serious organised rural crime; prevention and detection of household burglaries, etc.)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Having set my budget for 2013/14 and published the Police and Crime Plan at the end of March 2013, I have agreed a corporate framework for holding the Chief Constable to account for the delivery of the policing priorities and objectives contained in the Plan.  This involves:  </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A mixture of regular public and non-public meetings that involve both decision-making and scrutiny of policing performance, in respect of which agenda, reports and minutes of meetings are published on my website for public consumption – this is intended to facilitate public accountability of my performance in both holding the Chief Constable to account for the performance of the Force and my delivery of my Police and Crime Plan</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Regular informal liaison meetings with the Chief Constable at which current topical issues can be discussed, in private, to raise awareness of our respective concerns and establish a common shared response to significant issues and problems.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have a standing invitation to attend, as an observer, internal Force Performance Management meetings where I can understand more clearly the operational and community issues affecting Force performance at a local policing area level, and their local priorities, which helps inform the ongoing review of my Thames Valley-wide policing and crime priorities.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With the Chief Constable I have set up a Joint Independent Audit Committee which is charged with reviewing and testing the adequacy and effectiveness of the corporate governance framework and internal management control environment.  This committee reports to both me and the Chief Constable and is due to present </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to us </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its first ‘Annual Assurance Report’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">later this month (17</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> December).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have regular liaison meetings with HMIC to obtain an independent opinion on the performance of the Force.  HMIC inspection reports and Value for Money (VFM) Profiles contribute to my evidence base and inform my assessment of the performance of the Chief Constable and the Force.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I also take into account reports from the external auditor (Ernst and Young) that help inform my views on the quality of financial management arrangements and probity exercised by the Chief Constable and the Force.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An area that needs further development is the formal ‘Performance Development Review’ (PDR) process applicable to the Chief Constable to reflect the new governance arrangements following the introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCCs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the establishment of PCCs and chief constables as separate legal entities with specific respective roles and responsibilities.  This is a national issue that has been identified by the Association of Police and Crime Commissioners (APCC).</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">C</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of police and crime panels in holding their commissioners to account</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">First</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> may I point out that police and crime panels do not have a statutory responsibility to hold commissioners to account. The Home Secretary has made it clear that it is the electorate, through the ballot box, who holds their commissioner to account.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Instead, the statutory role and responsibility of police and crime panels, per s.28(6) of the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011, is to “... </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">review or scrutinise decisions made, or other actions taken, by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">police and crime commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in connection with the discharge of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">commissioner’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> functions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and to “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">make reports or recommendations to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">police and crime commissioner with respect to the discharge of the commissioner’s functions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, the general duty placed on panels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> concerning how they discharge their functions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (per s.28(2)) is that “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The functions of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">police and crime p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">anel must be exercised with a view to supporting the effective exercise of the functions of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">police and crime commisioner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Notwithstanding the above clarifications, my observations on the way the Thames Valley Police and Crime Panel has exercised its functions are as follows:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It has established </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">procedures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">determining and conducting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">business </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">together with a protocol covering the requests for information from my Office which are conducive to efficient and effective working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Panel received my draft Police and Crime Plan and subjected it to intensive, but fair, challenge as to the evidence base underpinning my policing and crime priorities and objectives.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Panel established a ‘Task and Finish’ group to scrutinise my budget plans </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in detail in order to inform its views and recommendations concerning my council tax precept proposal for 2013/14. This process also facilitated the Panel to form a view as to whether the proposed annual budget and medium term financial plan had allocated resources appropriately in accordance with priorities and objectives set out in my police and Crime Plan. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> helped ensure that I and the Panel had </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shared </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">confidence that the Plan had correctly identified and was properly addressing the ‘right’ priorities of the communities and stakeholders across the Thames Valley</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and that the associated objectives could be delivered within the reduced level of resources available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Panel’s work programme and business procedures ensure it is reviewing my performance in delivering the strategic objectives set out in my Police and Crime Plan in a methodical and mutually supportive manner.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  This process has introduced an independent performance monitoring regime that is effectively acting as an ‘early-warning’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> system to inform me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as much as the Panel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as to whether my objectives are being successfully achieved according to plan.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Finally, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here there has been tension between the Panel and myself, it has usually </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">involved the following</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, linked,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s:</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.3pt; padding-left:9.15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Panel seeking to extend its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">role and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">remit beyond its statutory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">duties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">attempting to scrutinise my intentions, rather than my decisions  and actions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effectively seeking to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">act as a consultative body </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with a view to approving or endorsing my proposals prior to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">taking decisions.  This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">creating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a greater volume of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inappropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">scrutiny </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bureaucratic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">activity for itself </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and my Office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the process that was not envisaged in the legislation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, at best,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may be viewed as inevitable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as all panels </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are likely to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> seek to enhance their status and influence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in order </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to justify their existence and give themselves credibility in the eyes of the public and media commentators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  However, this does not justify </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">such unilateral</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> extension</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the Panel’s role</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.3pt; padding-left:9.15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Panel seeking, inappropriately, to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">review or scrutinise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the performance of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">olice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> Force</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  The Panel has no remit to scrutinise the performance of the Chief Constable or the Force; that is my statutory responsibility. In this respect, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">actions and behaviour of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Panel gives the impression that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">default</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approach to exercising its functions is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to replicate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, inappropriately,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the role and responsibilities of the former </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thames Valley Police Authority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(of which a significant number of members </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">members of the Police </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and Crime Panel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.3pt; padding-left:9.15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Individual members of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Panel spends a disproportionate amount of time and effort scrutinising my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">intentions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and decisions on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">matters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and activities that directly affect their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">respective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> e.g. allocation of community safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">partnership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fund monies, commissioning of victim services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, with a view to protecting their local area rather than reviewing whether my decisions and actions are having a successful impact on the Thames Valley as a whole.   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nevertheless, Parliament was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">quite </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deliberate in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its decisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">creating Panels with a limited set of responsibilities, duties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> powers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ources.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  This was to avoid panels inadvertently usurping the role of the electorate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCC’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">D</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The division of functions and staff  between commissioners and chief constables following the Stage 2 transfers under the PRSR Act 2011</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:19.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.5pt"><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My ‘Stage 2 Staff Transfer Plan’ was submitted to the Home Secretary on the 9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> September 2013.  I have no</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> received confirmation that my Plan has been approved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in principle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the Ho